1776461684277499	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtDA		item.create	bn-27i	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\n`kb` is a Rust CLI-first tool that manages a personal, file-based knowledge base. The full design lives in `notes/plan.md` (in this repo). Two roots:\n\n- Code: `~/src/kb`\n- Data: `~/kb` (global) or `<project>/kb/` (project-scoped, e.g. `~/chief/consulting/kb/`)\n\nThe KB is compiled, not chatted with: ingest sources → incrementally compile a markdown wiki → answer questions into artifacts that cite their source material. Everything is local, file-based, git-friendly, Obsidian-compatible.\n\n# Goals\n\nShip a narrow end-to-end loop that is actually useful in daily research work:\n\n- ingest and compile roughly 100-300 sources without collapsing into full rebuilds\n- answer non-trivial questions into artifacts that cite source material clearly\n- `kb inspect <id>` exposes the full provenance chain from output back to source revisions\n- degrade gracefully when evidence is weak (surface uncertainty instead of inventing grounding)\n- result is readable directly in Obsidian or any markdown editor, no special tooling required\n\n# Reasoning / Justification\n\nTreats the system like a compiler rather than a chat app. Deterministic pipelines where possible, LLM calls only where they add real value (synthesis, extraction, rewrite). Provenance is the central product problem — every generated artifact records its input set, prompt hash, model name, and timestamp so the user can always ask \"why does this page exist, and what would rebuild it?\"\n\nNon-goals for v1: custom database, multi-user collaboration, cloud sync, Obsidian plugin as primary UI, fine-tuning, LLM directly editing arbitrary old files without guardrails.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\nRust workspace with these crates:\n\n- `kb-core`: domain types, file layout, manifests, hashing, provenance, dep graph, artifact metadata\n- `kb-llm`: model adapter traits, prompt rendering, execution wrappers, retry logic, token/accounting hooks\n- `kb-ingest`: source importers (local files, URLs, repos, images, PDFs) and metadata normalization\n- `kb-compile`: wiki compilation passes, summarization, concept extraction, backlinks, stale detection\n- `kb-query`: question planning, retrieval, artifact generation, answer sessions\n- `kb-lint`: integrity checks (citations, duplicates, broken links, stale indexes)\n- `kb-cli`: the `kb` binary\n\nStart as a single crate and split later if velocity matters, but internal module boundaries follow this shape from the start.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `kb init` creates a working KB root (global or project)\n- [ ] `kb ingest` handles local markdown files and readable web articles\n- [ ] `kb compile` produces source summaries, concept pages, and indexes incrementally\n- [ ] `kb ask` answers a question into `outputs/questions/<id>.md` with provenance frontmatter\n- [ ] `kb lint` catches broken links and missing citations\n- [ ] `kb inspect <id>` shows the full provenance chain\n- [ ] MVP runs on a real corpus (roughly 100k-500k words)\n\n# How This Serves Project Goals\n\nThis is the project itself. Delivering the narrow end-to-end loop is the whole goal of v1. Everything else (Phase 5 integrations, Phase 6 evaluation) depends on this loop existing and being trustworthy.","kind":"goal","title":"kb — personal knowledge base CLI (v1)"}	blake3:t1g7Mb4i07HOAlvqsxSJ6MkJh8NdQdnBT_FDlNqClok
1776461684441312	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtDQ		item.create	bn-1cs	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPhase 0 is the foundation phase. Nothing else in the plan works without a cargo workspace, shared domain types, config loading, and the primitives that keep mutating commands safe (atomic writes, root locks, JobRun skeletons). This phase has no LLM involvement — it's pure scaffolding.\n\n# Goals\n\nAfter Phase 0, `kb init` should create a working KB root and all downstream phases should have the core types and safety primitives they need.\n\n# Reasoning / Justification\n\nGetting these primitives right early prevents expensive rewrites. Atomic writes, root locks, and JobRun records are called out in the plan as load-bearing: they are what make interrupted jobs recoverable and keep manifests from corrupting under concurrent runs.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\nSingle cargo workspace with crate skeletons (can start as a single crate and split later). Focus on:\n\n- workspace layout + clap skeleton\n- domain type definitions (structs with serde)\n- filesystem helpers: root discovery, atomic write, advisory lock\n- `kb init` (only command that does not need an existing root)\n- managed-region marker + stable section-ID format (decided once, used everywhere)\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `cargo build` produces a `kb` binary\n- [ ] `kb init` creates a KB root with `kb.toml` and the documented directory layout\n- [ ] Root discovery walks up from cwd, falls back to `~/kb`, honors `--root`\n- [ ] Atomic write helper: temp file + rename, no partial writes under kill -9\n- [ ] Advisory root lock blocks concurrent mutating commands\n- [ ] JobRun skeleton writes start/status/end records under `state/jobs/`\n- [ ] Managed-region marker + section-ID format documented and implemented\n\n# How This Serves Project Goals\n\nPhase 0 is the floor that every later phase stands on. Without these primitives, the incremental build system cannot be trustworthy and provenance cannot be stable.","kind":"goal","parent":"bn-27i","title":"Phase 0 — Bootstrap: workspace, core types, kb init"}	blake3:4uXmS9ihj6uFXdkh48wpAHZCdmFj2BaswMyIuHyAD8E
1776461684596507	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtDg		item.create	bn-drw	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\n`kb-llm` is the adapter layer between `kb` and the agent harnesses that actually run models. The plan commits to subscription-based harnesses only — no direct API providers, no local model runners. Default is **opencode + openai/gpt-5.4**; Claude models must route through Claude Code per Anthropic's ToS.\n\nThe invocation contract is already in production in `~/src/chief/ws/default/src/runner/` and should be mirrored rather than reinvented.\n\n# Goals\n\nExpose a trait with the operations `kb` actually needs (summarize, extract concepts, answer questions, generate slides, health check) and two backends: opencode (default) and Claude Code (for Claude models).\n\n# Reasoning / Justification\n\n- **Subscription harnesses only:** amortizes existing agent subscriptions instead of per-token API bills.\n- **Claude Code mandatory for Claude:** Anthropic's ToS forbids running Claude subscription models through `opencode` or other third-party harnesses.\n- **Mirror chief's contract:** chief already solved the shell-out contract, ANSI stripping, timeout+SIGKILL, and prompt template rendering. Copy the patterns in `chief/ws/default/src/runner/opencode.rs:47-136` and `runner/templates.rs:127-186`.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Adapter trait with `summarize_document`, `extract_concepts`, `merge_concept_candidates`, `answer_question`, `generate_slides`, `run_health_check`.\n- opencode backend: invoke `opencode run --agent <name> [--session <id>] [--variant <v>] <prompt>`; prompt as positional arg; model via generated `opencode.json`; parse stdout by stripping ANSI + header lines starting with `>`.\n- Claude Code backend: shell out to `claude -p --output-format json` (chief's runner already uses this shape).\n- Router: if model family is Claude → Claude Code, else → opencode.\n- Timeouts: poll + SIGKILL (mirror chief's executor).\n- Prompt template loader: markdown files with `{{var}}` substitution, optional persona prefix.\n- Provenance capture: model, harness/runner version, latency, retries; note that opencode does not return token/cost in stdout.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Trait compiles with all six operations\n- [ ] opencode backend can run `summarize_document` end-to-end against a real `opencode` install\n- [ ] Claude Code backend can run `summarize_document` against real `claude`\n- [ ] Router picks the correct backend based on requested model\n- [ ] Timeouts kill the subprocess cleanly\n- [ ] Prompt template renderer handles `{{var}}` + persona prefix\n- [ ] ProvenanceRecord struct captures harness, model, latency, retry count\n\n# How This Serves Project Goals\n\nEvery synthesis step in the compile pipeline and every question answer flows through this adapter. Getting it right once means the rest of `kb` does not have to care which harness is running.","kind":"goal","parent":"bn-27i","title":"LLM adapter — opencode + Claude Code backends (kb-llm crate)"}	blake3:hjolvNX8jhDS22Meq7wOUViRNV1c_D6B7XMtKMzdSj0
1776461684754108	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtDw		item.create	bn-165	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPhase 1 makes `kb ingest` work for the MVP's two supported input types: local markdown/text files and readable web articles. Other input types (PDFs, repos, datasets, images) are explicitly deferred.\n\n# Goals\n\nAfter Phase 1, the user can run `kb ingest <path-or-url>...` and end up with stable SourceDocument IDs, immutable SourceRevision snapshots, and normalized markdown under `normalized/<doc-id>/`.\n\n# Reasoning / Justification\n\nIngest is independent of the LLM, so it can be built in parallel with the `kb-llm` adapter. Source ID stability is called out in the plan as a load-bearing invariant — IDs must survive refetches, so they can be tested without any model involvement.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Local file ingest: copy into `raw/inbox/` with sidecar metadata, hash content.\n- URL ingest: fetch via `reqwest`, extract readable content via `readability` or similar, convert to markdown.\n- Source ID minting: stable across refetches of the same logical source (URL or file path + content fingerprint).\n- Source revision hashing: changes when content changes materially.\n- Normalized writer: `normalized/<doc-id>/source.md`, `metadata.json`, `assets/`.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `kb ingest ./path/to/file.md` registers the file under `raw/` and produces a normalized record\n- [ ] `kb ingest https://example.com/article` fetches, extracts, converts to markdown\n- [ ] Re-ingesting the same source produces the same SourceDocument ID\n- [ ] Re-ingesting changed content produces a new SourceRevision ID\n- [ ] Normalized records include metadata (title, author, fetched_at, content_hash)\n\n# How This Serves Project Goals\n\nIngest is the top of the pipeline. Stable source IDs are what make citations meaningful and incremental compilation possible — everything downstream assumes Phase 1's invariants.","kind":"goal","parent":"bn-27i","title":"Phase 1 — Ingest: local files + URLs into stable source records"}	blake3:UZDrqxfo6ucoavis_J7NUofha2Pwi7DVRzYm1hYGsWI
1776461684907565	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtEA		item.create	bn-14j	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPhase 2 is the most important technical feature of the project. `kb compile` runs incremental compilation passes that turn normalized sources into compiled wiki pages, with full provenance and stale detection.\n\n# Goals\n\nAfter Phase 2, `kb compile` behaves like a lightweight build system: hash inputs, build a dep graph, detect the minimal stale set, rerun only affected passes, record BuildRecords.\n\n# Reasoning / Justification\n\nIf compilation is not incremental, the tool collapses into full rebuilds once the corpus grows past ~100 sources. The plan explicitly optimizes for a workflow that stays useful in daily research.\n\nPass order (from plan):\n1. ingest/normalize (Phase 1)\n2. extract metadata and source summaries\n3. create/update source pages in `wiki/sources/`\n4. extract candidate concepts and aliases\n5. merge/update concept pages in `wiki/concepts/`\n6. regenerate backlinks and index pages\n7. run lint passes (Phase 4)\n8. optionally generate queued outputs (Phase 3)\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Manifest/hash tracker: `state/manifest.json`, `state/hashes.json`.\n- Dep graph: `state/graph.json` — edges from source docs → normalized → wiki pages → outputs.\n- Stale detection: walk graph from changed nodes, mark downstream stale.\n- Pass orchestrator: topological execution of stale passes; each pass writes a BuildRecord.\n- Generated markdown uses managed-region markers + stable section IDs (defined in Phase 0).\n- Prompt template changes invalidate only the outputs that depend on those prompts (template hash in BuildRecord).\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Second `kb compile` with no input changes is a no-op (zero LLM calls)\n- [ ] Changing one source triggers recompile of that source's page + affected concept pages\n- [ ] Every generated file has frontmatter with source_ids, source_revision_ids, build_record_id\n- [ ] Managed regions are replaced cleanly without clobbering surrounding content\n- [ ] Lexical index built over titles, aliases, summaries, key headings\n\n# How This Serves Project Goals\n\nThis is the \"compiler\" in \"treat the system like a compiler, not a chat app.\" Getting incremental build + provenance right here is what makes the whole system trustworthy.","kind":"goal","parent":"bn-27i","title":"Phase 2 — Compile: manifests, summaries, concept pages, lexical index"}	blake3:M4nToayFQp_EA1R6WVCtaSb4WP39TE8GETv7AdkdWQk
1776461685062892	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtEQ		item.create	bn-3b4	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPhase 3 implements `kb ask <question>`. Questions are first-class tracked objects, not ephemeral chats. Each question produces a durable artifact with full provenance.\n\n# Goals\n\nAfter Phase 3, the user can ask questions and get grounded markdown answers under `outputs/questions/<id>.md`, with retrieval plans saved for debugging.\n\n# Reasoning / Justification\n\nThe plan explicitly rejects a pure-RAG approach. A layered lexical strategy (rank cheap, read deep for top candidates) is simpler, deterministic enough to debug, and keeps the v1 scope tight. Saving the retrieval plan makes it possible to ask \"why did this question read these files and ignore others?\"\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Question records with timestamp, requested format, user query.\n- Retrieval planner: rank candidates using lexical index (titles, aliases, tags, summaries, key headings).\n- Context assembly: pull top-ranked source/wiki material into a token budget.\n- Artifact generator: markdown memo format first; Marp slide deck, JSON report, plot data spec later.\n- Writer: `outputs/questions/<id>.md` with frontmatter + sidecar metadata.\n- `kb search <query>`: lexical search over the same index (debug aid).\n- `kb inspect <id>`: print metadata, dependency edges, citations, generating jobs, freshness.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `kb ask \"question\"` produces a markdown artifact with at least one citation\n- [ ] Retrieval plan is saved with each question (candidate set, ranking reasons, token budget)\n- [ ] `kb search \"query\"` returns candidate source IDs + wiki IDs\n- [ ] `kb inspect <id>` resolves metadata and the provenance chain\n\n# How This Serves Project Goals\n\nThis closes the MVP loop: \"ingest → compile → ask.\" Until this works, the tool is not useful in daily research even if the plumbing is perfect.","kind":"goal","parent":"bn-27i","title":"Phase 3 — Ask: retrieval + question artifacts with provenance"}	blake3:3efZnAvjOsOpnSBdpph6wdYLu3S6DyaeZKNbK1HBgb8
1776461685217105	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtEg		item.create	bn-1ji	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPhase 4 adds integrity checks and operator-facing visibility. Main risk the plan calls out: state drift and low-trust outputs that still look polished. Lint is the counter to that.\n\n# Goals\n\n- `kb lint` catches broken links, missing citations, duplicate concepts, orphan pages, stale derived artifacts.\n- `kb status` surfaces counts, freshness, recent jobs, failures, changed inputs.\n- `kb doctor` validates config, model access, filesystem permissions, prompt templates, external tools.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Broken-link checker flags wiki→wiki and wiki→source links that do not resolve\n- [ ] Missing-citation checker flags synthesized sections without source references\n- [ ] Duplicate concept / title warnings reach the user via `kb review` queue\n- [ ] Orphan and stale detection work correctly after inputs change\n- [ ] Interrupted-job detection surfaces recovery guidance\n\n# How This Serves Project Goals\n\nWithout lint, trust erodes quickly as the corpus grows. This phase is what keeps the KB honest.","kind":"goal","parent":"bn-27i","title":"Phase 4 — Lint, status, and doctor"}	blake3:yFhvWfuAcZUW19vCQgFfWJjKu_In6QIduGrte-XNO74
1776461685368037	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtEw		item.create	bn-3dc	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPhase 5 adds the review/promotion workflow and publishing flows. The plan is explicit that generated output is not automatically trusted just because it exists — `kb ask` writes artifacts with sidecar metadata, and promotion into `wiki/` goes through explicit review.\n\n# Goals\n\n- `kb review` lets the user inspect and approve/reject pending promotions, concept merges, alias merges.\n- `kb publish <target>` syncs selected artifacts into repo-local `notes/` with backlinks preserved.\n- Stable CLI JSON output across commands (for agent harness integration).\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] ReviewItem queue records proposed destination, citations, affected pages\n- [ ] `kb review` can approve/reject items\n- [ ] Approved promotions write through the managed-region contract\n- [ ] Rejected promotions stay in `outputs/` but are marked as rejected\n- [ ] `kb publish` syncs artifacts into a project's `notes/` folder\n- [ ] All commands support `--json` with a documented schema\n\n# How This Serves Project Goals\n\nReview gates are what prevent synthesized outputs from silently becoming \"wiki facts.\" Publishing makes the KB reach beyond its own root into projects where the work actually happens.","kind":"goal","parent":"bn-27i","title":"Phase 5 — Publish, review queue, and integrations"}	blake3:u0hdbpgnK_JXBicL3eR0XVb15A7IQVQRaqm4vX_0GE4
1776461685521626	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtFA		item.create	bn-1lv	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPhase 6 turns the built system into something trustworthy under load. Many of the real product risks (concept explosion, weak answers that look polished, citation drift) only show up once the corpus and question set get messy.\n\n# Goals\n\n- Benchmark set of gold questions against a real corpus\n- Measured compile time, incremental rebuild time, answer grounding quality\n- Prompt templates and invalidation rules tuned against observed failures\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Gold question set exists (at least 20 questions with expected citation sets)\n- [ ] Compile time and incremental rebuild time are measured on a real corpus\n- [ ] Answer grounding quality is measured (e.g. citation coverage, hallucination rate)\n- [ ] At least one iteration of prompt tuning based on failure analysis\n\n# How This Serves Project Goals\n\nShipping v1 without evaluation means shipping a system whose failure modes the user does not know. This phase converts \"it runs\" into \"it is worth keeping in the loop.\"","kind":"goal","parent":"bn-27i","title":"Phase 6 — Evaluation and hardening"}	blake3:yd6GHgTBDf06QZ3SlD3lKyhb6BsWKw4u0VL7ZRPMz5A
1776461774293099	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtFQ		item.create	bn-f88	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPlan commits to a workspace split: `kb-core`, `kb-llm`, `kb-ingest`, `kb-compile`, `kb-query`, `kb-lint`, `kb-cli`. Can start as a single crate and split later, but module boundaries should follow the target shape from day one.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Root `Cargo.toml` with `[workspace]` section\n- Create `crates/kb-core`, `crates/kb-llm`, `crates/kb-ingest`, `crates/kb-compile`, `crates/kb-query`, `crates/kb-lint`, `crates/kb-cli`\n- Wire common deps: `clap`, `anyhow`, `thiserror`, `serde`, `serde_json`, `toml`, `blake3`, `tracing`, `tracing-subscriber`\n- `kb-cli` produces the `kb` binary\n- `.gitignore` for `target/` and local-only state\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `cargo build --workspace` succeeds\n- [ ] `cargo run --bin kb -- --version` prints a version\n- [ ] Crate dependency direction is one-way: `kb-cli` depends on everything; `kb-core` depends on nothing internal","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1cs","title":"Set up Rust cargo workspace + crate skeletons"}	blake3:Tfag7h92EEpEySQExLBhuTJl-V1V4zVr2vtgcyRlI3Y
1776461774445250	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtFg		item.create	bn-36d	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nAll phases depend on a shared vocabulary of entities. Plan enumerates: SourceDocument, SourceRevision, NormalizedDocument, WikiPage, Concept, Question, Artifact, Citation, BuildRecord, JobRun, ReviewItem.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\nEach struct is `Serialize + Deserialize`, includes:\n\n- stable ID\n- created/updated timestamps\n- source hashes\n- model/tool version used (where applicable)\n- prompt template hash (where applicable)\n- dependency list\n- output paths\n- status enum: `fresh`, `stale`, `failed`, `needs_review`\n\nIdentity rules worth encoding in the types:\n- `SourceDocument.id` is stable across refetches of the same logical source\n- `SourceRevision.id` changes whenever fetched content changes materially\n- `Citation` points at a `SourceRevision` + locator (heading anchor, line/char span, page, asset ref)\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] All 11 entity structs defined with serde derives\n- [ ] Shared `Status` enum with the four states\n- [ ] `Citation` supports heading anchor, line/char span, page number, asset reference locators\n- [ ] Unit tests for round-trip serialization","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1cs","title":"Define core domain types in kb-core"}	blake3:VC7wMMEF0kXoqxF_uJPnPA1QC_806lb3eF06kd0cq3c
1776461774594864	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtFw		item.create	bn-2fr	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPlan supports two scopes: global `~/kb` and project-scoped `<project>/kb/` (e.g. `~/chief/consulting/kb/`). Discovery must work regardless of which scope the user is in.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\nRules (for any command other than `kb init`):\n1. If `--root <path>` is passed, use it\n2. Walk up from `$PWD` looking for a directory containing `kb/kb.toml`; if found, that `kb/` dir is the root\n3. Fall back to `~/kb` if it exists\n4. Otherwise fail with a clear error pointing to `kb init`\n\nProduce a `KbRoot` handle that downstream code consumes.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `--root /some/path` forces that root\n- [ ] Running inside `~/chief/consulting/` discovers `~/chief/consulting/kb/`\n- [ ] Running outside any project discovers `~/kb`\n- [ ] Missing root produces actionable error message\n- [ ] Tests cover all four branches","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1cs","title":"KB root discovery (walk up, fallback to ~/kb, --root override)"}	blake3:dzH972F8fXjW7qoO0TtpOfPRTZhP0O1iqDxqRmsV0fU
1776461774748007	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtGA		item.create	bn-10p	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\n`kb init` is the only command that does not need an existing root — it creates one.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Default target is cwd; `--root` overrides\n- Write `kb.toml` with sensible defaults (default backend = opencode, default model = openai/gpt-5.4)\n- Create directory skeleton: `raw/{inbox,web,papers,repos,datasets,images}`, `normalized/`, `wiki/{concepts,sources,projects,timelines,people}`, `outputs/{questions,reports,slides,figures}`, `reviews/{promotions,merges}`, `prompts/`, `state/{indexes,jobs,locks}`, `cache/`, `logs/`, `trash/`\n- `wiki/index.md` with a managed stub\n- Refuse to init if `kb.toml` already exists (use `--force` to overwrite)\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `kb init` in an empty dir produces a valid KB\n- [ ] `kb init` refuses to overwrite existing `kb.toml` without `--force`\n- [ ] Default `kb.toml` references opencode + openai/gpt-5.4","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1cs","title":"Implement kb init command"}	blake3:8vWkkn421YRyoE1mM42yG2uYPEONncIzR-zFW86Hews
1776461774903424	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtGQ		item.create	bn-3ac	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPlan enumerates config areas: data roots, default/fallback model, token/cost limits, enabled ingestion backends, prompt template directory, publish targets, lint thresholds, artifact defaults, retry/backoff, per-command budgets, review policy.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `Config` struct with serde; nested sections mirror chief's `.chief.toml` style\n- `[llm]` section with `default_runner`, `default_model`, per-runner overrides\n- `[llm.runners.opencode]` with `command`, `model`, `tools_*` flags\n- `[llm.runners.claude]` for Claude Code backend\n- `[compile]`, `[ask]`, `[lint]`, `[publish]` sections with task-specific defaults\n- `[review]` policy defaults\n- Load order: kb.toml → env var overrides → CLI flag overrides\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Default config from `kb init` loads cleanly\n- [ ] Missing optional fields fall back to defaults\n- [ ] Invalid config produces errors pointing at the offending key","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1cs","title":"Config loader for kb.toml"}	blake3:Sbdtf8a8Cluor5eyMlqsEyiOn6JCUxbpVy1QPWv2e8M
1776461775050921	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtGg		item.create	bn-2cp	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPlan calls for writing new artifacts to temporary paths first, then atomically renaming into place. This is what keeps a kill -9 mid-compile from leaving half-written files.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `atomic_write(path, contents)` writes to `<path>.tmp.<pid>.<rand>`, fsyncs, then renames over target\n- On Windows: fall back to remove-then-rename (but project is Linux-first)\n- Propagate IO errors with context (path in error)\n- Helper should also ensure parent directory exists\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Writing to a nonexistent target creates it atomically\n- [ ] Interrupting mid-write leaves old target intact (test with SIGKILL on a child process)\n- [ ] Parent dir is created if missing","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1cs","title":"Atomic write helper (temp + rename)"}	blake3:52WvD20-qdJnFMfYnRvs5kFNgatbYAawWBcb5Hi1-j8
1776461775200206	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtGw		item.create	bn-3nl	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPlan: only one mutating job should hold the KB root lock at a time. This prevents two concurrent `kb compile` runs from corrupting manifests or partially overwriting outputs.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- File-based advisory lock under `state/locks/root.lock` using `fcntl`-style advisory locking (crate `fs2` or `fd-lock`)\n- `KbLock::acquire(root, timeout)` returns a guard whose Drop releases the lock\n- Timeout is configurable; default 5s (matches chief's `lock.timeout_ms`)\n- Lock includes metadata: command, pid, started_at — readable for diagnostics\n- Read-only commands (`kb search`, `kb inspect`, `kb status`) do not take the lock\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Two concurrent mutating commands serialize correctly\n- [ ] Lock release on panic / process death (OS-level advisory lock)\n- [ ] Lock metadata file is readable when lock is held\n- [ ] Read-only commands run without blocking","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1cs","title":"Advisory root lock for mutating commands"}	blake3:3u3XHseeMcEFdVmG7fKeHoBA0leUP34bGqaTjzQBqlo
1776461775352142	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtHA		item.create	bn-3km	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nEvery mutating command writes a `JobRun` manifest before changing outputs. Interrupted jobs must be detectable and recoverable on the next `compile` or `doctor`.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `JobRun` struct: id, command, started_at, ended_at, status (running / succeeded / failed / interrupted), logs_path, affected_outputs\n- Create file under `state/jobs/<job-id>.json` at start with status=running\n- Update with status=succeeded or status=failed at end\n- On next mutating command, detect any `running` JobRun that is stale (no matching pid, or pid not alive) and mark it interrupted\n- Logs per job stream to `state/jobs/<job-id>.log`\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Each mutating command produces a JobRun record\n- [ ] Interrupted runs are detected and flagged on next invocation\n- [ ] `kb status` can list recent JobRuns","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1cs","title":"JobRun skeleton: start, status, end records"}	blake3:ldhaWa9654imCXCn3dCq_DFYGXfHf9ZoZS7K9o1TDgA
1776461775503069	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtHQ		item.create	bn-347	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nThis is one of the two contracts called out during planning as load-bearing: every compile pass depends on the managed-region format and section-ID scheme, and changing it later means rewriting generated files.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\nDecide on and implement:\n\n- **Managed-region marker format.** Proposed: HTML-comment fences like `<!-- kb:begin id=summary hash=<h> -->` / `<!-- kb:end id=summary -->`. Invisible in Obsidian, recognized by the rewriter.\n- **Section ID scheme.** Proposed: stable slugs derived from first-assignment title; once assigned, the slug survives title renames. Stored in frontmatter `sections: { summary: {...}, background: {...} }` or inline via marker attributes.\n- Rewriter replaces only content inside matching markers; unknown content outside managed regions is preserved.\n- Citations can reference `<page>#<section-id>`.\n\nWrite a short spec doc under `notes/managed_regions.md` covering the decision.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Spec documented in notes/\n- [ ] Parser recognizes managed-region fences and extracts regions\n- [ ] Rewriter replaces a region in-place without touching surrounding content\n- [ ] Section IDs survive title changes (persisted in frontmatter or marker)","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1cs","title":"Managed-region marker + stable section-ID format"}	blake3:TR6ZAEegrc9dKlI_VMHh45QkWkefgwJibijF4P5GkFg
1776461775656116	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtHg		item.create	bn-19j	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nEvery generated file has frontmatter with id, type, title, status, source_document_ids, source_revision_ids, generated_at, generated_by, build_record_id. This data is read by lint, inspect, and compile passes.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Small custom parser or serde-yaml-based approach; plan notes either is fine\n- Preserve unknown keys on round-trip (so manual additions do not get dropped)\n- Helpers: `read_frontmatter(&Path) -> (Meta, body)`, `write_frontmatter(&Path, Meta, body)`\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Reading a file with frontmatter returns structured metadata + body\n- [ ] Writing a file preserves unknown frontmatter keys\n- [ ] Round-trip is byte-stable for the managed fields","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1cs","title":"Frontmatter read/write helpers"}	blake3:160ZUzLoCNri4wp9sKQyuqCoQqJRLQaHg1SnZmvry8w
1776461775809739	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtHw		item.create	bn-2dz	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPlan uses blake3 for content hashes that drive source revision IDs, stale detection, and prompt-template invalidation.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Thin wrapper: `hash_bytes(&[u8]) -> Hash`, `hash_file(&Path) -> Hash`, `hash_many(&[&[u8]]) -> Hash` for composite hashing\n- `Hash` type wraps the blake3 digest and serializes as hex\n- Used by: source revisions, normalized content, prompt templates, build records\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] All three helpers implemented\n- [ ] Hash type serializes as hex string\n- [ ] Same input produces same hash across runs (obvious but worth a test)","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1cs","title":"Blake3-based hashing helpers"}	blake3:2S9dnG5WWv12C1Onx0COfDyi9DC7LPh4XOCNFLSgAKU
1776461775961112	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtIA		item.create	bn-2kv	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nCLI surface from the plan: `init`, `ingest`, `compile`, `ask`, `lint`, `doctor`, `status`, `publish`, plus follow-ons `search`, `inspect`, `review`. Global flags: `--root`, `--format md|marp|json|png`, `--model`, `--since`, `--dry-run`, `--json`, `--force`, `--review`.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `clap` derive macros for each subcommand\n- Global flags on the top-level command\n- Each subcommand stubbed to print \"not implemented\" and exit nonzero\n- `--json` toggles structured output globally\n- Tracing subscriber configured with sensible defaults (respect `RUST_LOG`)\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `kb --help` shows all planned subcommands\n- [ ] Each subcommand has a help page\n- [ ] Global flags parse on any subcommand\n- [ ] Exit codes: 0 success, 1 user error, 2 internal error","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1cs","title":"Top-level clap CLI skeleton with global flags"}	blake3:kfqp0eID2WxORCp3ZbRVPOTq88fAHKir7fzJRLR9FXo
1776461776122586	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtIQ		item.create	bn-33w	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPlan testing strategy calls for CLI snapshot tests (`insta`), end-to-end fixture tests with small synthetic corpora, and a `tests/fixtures/` directory with markdown files, HTML pages, and images.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `tests/fixtures/corpus-tiny/`: ~5 markdown files, 1 HTML page, 1 image, covering edge cases (unicode, heading anchors, images, long tokens)\n- `tests/common/mod.rs` helpers: `make_temp_kb()`, `kb_cmd()` returning `assert_cmd::Command` with `--root` set to the temp dir\n- Snapshot tests via `insta` for deterministic command output\n- `tempfile` for per-test tempdirs\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Tiny fixture corpus exists and is documented\n- [ ] `cargo test` runs a smoke test that inits a KB in a tempdir\n- [ ] At least one `insta` snapshot passing","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1cs","title":"tests/fixtures scaffold + assert_cmd+insta setup"}	blake3:KZWX6swrpXoGiXr98gvmHIg24n1J0dC9DqjuArqgSRE
1776461826679885	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtIg		item.create	bn-11a	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nAll six operations the rest of `kb` needs: `summarize_document`, `extract_concepts`, `merge_concept_candidates`, `answer_question`, `generate_slides`, `run_health_check`.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Trait with async or sync methods (pick sync first — simpler, matches chief's runner shape)\n- Each method takes a request struct + returns a response struct + `ProvenanceRecord`\n- Errors use `thiserror` with classes: transport, timeout, parse, auth, rate_limit, other\n- Trait does not know about specific harnesses — backends implement it\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Trait compiles in isolation\n- [ ] Each method has doc comments describing expected inputs/outputs\n- [ ] Error type covers the classes above","kind":"task","parent":"bn-drw","title":"Define LlmAdapter trait in kb-llm"}	blake3:2ZeylwDZOWy1m9kHkK-nrBQQfphVixsmx-aqT9FSrBM
1776461826836197	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtIw		item.create	bn-1v3	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nEvery generated artifact records the input set, prompt hash, model name, and timestamp. Backends must expose provider/model name, harness/runner version, token usage (where available), retry counts, latency.\n\nImportant gap: opencode does NOT report token/cost in stdout. Record the gap honestly rather than inventing numbers.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n`ProvenanceRecord` struct:\n- `harness: String` (e.g. \"opencode\", \"claude-code\")\n- `harness_version: Option<String>`\n- `model: String`\n- `prompt_template_name: String`\n- `prompt_template_hash: Hash`\n- `prompt_render_hash: Hash` (after variable substitution)\n- `started_at`, `ended_at`, `latency_ms`\n- `retries: u32`\n- `tokens: Option<TokenUsage>` (None when harness does not report)\n- `cost_estimate: Option<f64>`\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Struct compiles with serde\n- [ ] Serializes to JSON with nulls for missing tokens\n- [ ] Included in every backend's response path","kind":"task","parent":"bn-drw","title":"ProvenanceRecord: capture harness, model, latency, retries"}	blake3:_vPGzD2q1O_ryCnoNqxHAyV-9l_Zjp2gpwikJypXaM0
1776461826993849	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtJA		item.create	bn-2ik	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nMirror chief's production contract in `~/src/chief/ws/default/src/runner/opencode.rs:47-136`. Default backend for all non-Claude models; default model `openai/gpt-5.4`.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Invoke as: `opencode run --agent <name> [--session <id>] [--variant <v>] <prompt>`\n- Prompt passed as positional arg (NOT stdin)\n- Model selection: write a per-call `opencode.json` config with model + tool toggles + provider; point opencode at it (see `chief/.../runner/config.rs`)\n- Capture stdout, parse via `strip_ansi_header()` equivalent:\n  - strip ANSI escapes via regex `\\x1b\\[[0-9;]*m`\n  - drop leading blank lines and lines starting with `>`\n  - trim the rest\n- Stateless by default; `--session` available for future use\n- Tool flags (read/write/edit/bash) go in the JSON config, not CLI args\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Can run `summarize_document` against a real `opencode` install end-to-end\n- [ ] opencode.json is generated correctly with default model `openai/gpt-5.4`\n- [ ] Response parser handles chief's observed output format\n- [ ] Failure path surfaces opencode stderr in the error","kind":"task","parent":"bn-drw","title":"opencode backend (default)"}	blake3:-QXGdBbqG5WAuT6KJDCrrlYgeSjkAC4eS1Vg-EFdH1A
1776461827147223	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtJQ		item.create	bn-123	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nAnthropic ToS forbids running Claude subscription models through third-party harnesses like opencode. Claude calls MUST go through the `claude` CLI.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Invoke as `claude -p --output-format json <prompt>` (matches chief's runners.claude config)\n- Parse the structured JSON response\n- Capture any token/cost metadata Claude Code returns\n- Honor Claude Code permission modes where relevant (default mode is fine for prompt-only calls)\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Can run `summarize_document` against a real `claude` install\n- [ ] JSON response parsed into `ProvenanceRecord` (including tokens if Claude Code provides them)\n- [ ] Timeouts and subprocess kill work the same way as opencode backend","kind":"task","parent":"bn-drw","title":"Claude Code backend (required for Claude models)"}	blake3:5LVMFTJvsCO6eO7KzJ1z83doj1QcNuh5rzQ3TBcIr3Q
1776461827299608	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtJg		item.create	bn-p8b	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nThe model routing rule is simple but load-bearing: if the model family is Claude, the call MUST go through Claude Code (ToS), otherwise it goes through opencode.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `Router` holds configured backends and a default\n- Given a model string, match `claude-*` / `anthropic/*` / `claude/*` → Claude Code backend\n- Everything else → opencode backend (or `pi` when configured)\n- Selection is based on model string, not caller preference — callers cannot override\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Router picks Claude Code for `claude-opus-4-7`, `anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6`, etc.\n- [ ] Router picks opencode for `openai/gpt-5.4`, `gemini-*`, etc.\n- [ ] Caller cannot force a Claude model through opencode (routing is authoritative)","kind":"task","parent":"bn-drw","title":"Backend router (Claude -> Claude Code, else -> opencode)"}	blake3:ZyWeZL6hSql5UeFeKerkw7fo7u7FF_cjzUONWZq6urA
1776461827454929	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtJw		item.create	bn-1oq	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nMirror chief's executor timeout handling. Long-running or stuck harness subprocesses must be killable.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Spawn child process with separate threads reading stdout/stderr (prevents pipe deadlock on full buffers — chief does this in `executor.rs:282-313`)\n- Timeout enforced by polling exit status; on timeout send SIGKILL (not SIGTERM — chief found SIGTERM unreliable against some children)\n- Timeout value configurable per-operation in `kb.toml`\n- On timeout, surface partial captured stdout/stderr in the error\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] A 100-second stub command killed correctly by a 2-second timeout\n- [ ] Timeout error includes partial stdout/stderr\n- [ ] No zombie child processes after timeout","kind":"task","parent":"bn-drw","title":"Subprocess timeout + SIGKILL pattern"}	blake3:DWRj9KWu7M6D5QZEy3tJXXGX1RIphIY3K282h3yPum4
1776461827609774	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtKA		item.create	bn-11v	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nMirror chief's `runner/templates.rs:127-186`. Prompts live as markdown files, render with simple `{{var}}` substitution, optional persona prefix.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Templates under `<kb-root>/prompts/*.md`; personas under `<kb-root>/prompts/personas/*.md`\n- Fallback to bundled defaults via `include_str!()` when project file is absent (matches chief)\n- Renderer: regex `\\{\\{(\\w+)\\}\\}` → HashMap lookup; missing vars render as empty string (matches chief behavior; safer than panicking)\n- Persona prepended with `\\n\\n---\\n\\n` separator\n- Template + persona hash captured in ProvenanceRecord so prompt changes invalidate dependent outputs\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Can load a project template, falling back to bundled default\n- [ ] `{{var}}` substitution handles missing vars gracefully\n- [ ] Persona prefix added correctly\n- [ ] Hash of rendered prompt is stable across runs given same inputs","kind":"task","parent":"bn-drw","title":"Prompt template loader + {{var}} renderer"}	blake3:9SVNV7GggiZVb8k42FN7dFDObpMYrbOcu5wQisn3pMU
1776461827761172	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtKQ		item.create	bn-1lp	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\n`kb doctor` validates model access. Each backend should expose a cheap round-trip that proves the harness is installed, reachable, and can run a trivial prompt.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- opencode health check: `opencode run --agent <default> \"respond with OK\"` with 10-second timeout\n- Claude Code health check: `claude -p --output-format json \"respond with OK\"` with 10-second timeout\n- Returns latency, model used, and harness version if discoverable\n- Does not count toward regular provenance records\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Health check succeeds when harness is working\n- [ ] Missing harness binary produces actionable error (e.g. \"opencode not on PATH\")\n- [ ] Timeout works for non-responsive harness","kind":"task","parent":"bn-drw","title":"run_health_check operation for kb doctor"}	blake3:qzsTI-ApcfQhSwddugC_CQSW-6fbqf32T46TOcqBOro
1776461858965500	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtKg		item.create	bn-1fi	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nMVP input type #1: local markdown/text files. User runs `kb ingest ./notes/article.md` and ends up with a SourceDocument registered under `raw/`.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Accept one or more paths (files or directories); directories walk via `ignore` crate honoring `.gitignore`\n- Copy file into `raw/inbox/<source-id>/` with original filename preserved\n- Hash content with blake3\n- Write sidecar metadata: original_path, size, mtime, content_hash, imported_at\n- Return the SourceDocument for downstream normalization\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `kb ingest ./file.md` registers the file and produces metadata sidecar\n- [ ] Directory ingest walks files respecting `.gitignore`\n- [ ] Re-ingesting an unchanged file is idempotent (same SourceDocument ID)\n- [ ] Re-ingesting changed content produces a new SourceRevision","kind":"task","parent":"bn-165","title":"Local file ingest (copy into raw/, create source record)"}	blake3:vNg-z_NCNA-BvkRWphsvapLuy7aidXEfK8JGzfLELtU
1776461859127740	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtKw		item.create	bn-1qe	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nMVP input type #2: readable web articles. User runs `kb ingest https://example.com/article` and ends up with a normalized markdown record plus original HTML snapshot.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Fetch via `reqwest` with a reasonable UA string, follow redirects, 30-second timeout\n- Store raw HTML under `raw/web/<source-id>/page.html` with headers in `page.headers.json`\n- Extract readable content via `readability` crate (or similar) → HTML subset\n- Convert HTML → markdown via a library (e.g. `html2md`) or a small wrapper\n- Retain images: download linked images into `assets/` referenced from the markdown\n- Title extracted from `<title>` or first H1\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Can fetch a typical blog post URL\n- [ ] Raw HTML is preserved alongside the extracted markdown\n- [ ] Images are downloaded and referenced with relative paths\n- [ ] Retries on transient failures (up to 3x with backoff), fail cleanly otherwise","kind":"task","parent":"bn-165","title":"URL ingest: fetch + HTML-to-markdown"}	blake3:S84LUd1nDLz_Cd0UhedbucL8PMLrA_NXx-KLMJEWS3o
1776461859295504	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtLA		item.create	bn-apa	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nSource identity rules from the plan:\n- `SourceDocument.id` is stable across refetches of the same logical source\n- `SourceRevision.id` changes when fetched content changes materially\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- For files: `SourceDocument.id` = stable hash of canonicalized absolute path (so path moves break ID — acceptable; user can re-register)\n- For URLs: `SourceDocument.id` = stable hash of normalized URL (lowercase scheme+host, path, sorted query params)\n- `SourceRevision.id` = blake3 of content bytes\n- Both IDs use a short-form prefix (e.g. `src-<8chars>`, `rev-<8chars>`) plus collision check\n- Re-ingesting produces same SourceDocument.id; new SourceRevision only when content hash changes\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] File re-ingest produces same SourceDocument ID\n- [ ] URL re-fetch with unchanged content reuses the previous revision\n- [ ] URL re-fetch with changed content produces a new revision\n- [ ] Normalization rules documented (so the ID scheme is reproducible from spec)","kind":"task","parent":"bn-165","title":"Source ID minting + revision hashing"}	blake3:wqVcgdXRMYI3our-LeyW-WgOcFN7HLNd5Tcw7cQ3cew
1776461859460201	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtLQ		item.create	bn-1x0	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nNormalized records are the clean, tool-friendly representation of source content. Later compile passes read from here, not from `raw/`.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\nPer normalized doc write:\n- `normalized/<doc-id>/source.md` — the markdown body\n- `normalized/<doc-id>/metadata.json` — structured metadata (title, author, fetched_at, original_url, content_hash, source_revision_id, language)\n- `normalized/<doc-id>/assets/` — images/files referenced by source.md via relative paths\n- All writes via atomic write helper\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Writing produces the three artifacts atomically\n- [ ] Metadata JSON round-trips through domain type\n- [ ] Asset references in source.md resolve correctly","kind":"task","parent":"bn-165","title":"NormalizedDocument writer (normalized/<doc-id>/)"}	blake3:IRVPhj5mJHk0OUOkWjoEd--4jig4T_6oW1Raq4Vt4XU
1776461859620871	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtLg		item.create	bn-1s6	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nTies together local ingest + URL ingest + source ID minting + normalized writer into the `kb ingest <path-or-url>...` subcommand.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Accepts one or more arguments; each is auto-detected as file / directory / URL\n- Runs under a JobRun + root lock\n- Progress output shows per-source status\n- `--dry-run` prints what would be ingested without writing\n- `--json` emits structured per-source results\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `kb ingest file.md https://example.com dir/` handles all three in one run\n- [ ] Summary at the end shows new sources, new revisions, and skipped\n- [ ] `--dry-run` makes no filesystem changes","kind":"task","parent":"bn-165","title":"kb ingest command wiring (batch mode, status output)"}	blake3:qJT9Ne2c4xI_Ajvvk427VDfA9n2jBlZWBrz40D6qyIQ
1776461928274507	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtLw		item.create	bn-18r	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nThe manifest is the source of truth for what's been built and from what. The hashes file records input hashes so we can detect changes.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `Manifest` struct: map of artifact path → BuildRecord\n- `Hashes` struct: map of input path → blake3 hash\n- Both persisted atomically via the helper\n- Loaded once at compile start, mutated in memory, written on success\n- On failure or interruption, old files remain intact\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Second run with no changes produces identical manifest\n- [ ] Changing a source updates hashes and triggers rebuild of dependents\n- [ ] Corrupt manifest is detected at load time with a clear error","kind":"task","parent":"bn-14j","title":"Manifest + hash tracker (state/manifest.json, state/hashes.json)"}	blake3:iJl8vxGeSf9vjiZFm50WYB1whxFvpLhXGeN6GGZmi-c
1776461928433311	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtMA		item.create	bn-11p	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nEdges: source docs → normalized docs → wiki source pages → wiki concept pages → index/backlink pages → outputs. Also: prompt templates → generated content that used them.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `Graph` is a DAG of NodeId → {inputs: [NodeId], outputs: [NodeId]}\n- NodeIds reference artifact paths or prompt template hashes\n- Built as each pass declares its inputs/outputs to the orchestrator\n- Persisted as JSON for diagnostics (`kb inspect <id>` reads it)\n- Cycle detection at write time (should be impossible given pass order, but assert it)\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Graph correctly captures source → page → index chain\n- [ ] Prompt template change propagates to all pages that used that template\n- [ ] Cycle detection runs on every write","kind":"task","parent":"bn-14j","title":"Dependency graph builder (state/graph.json)"}	blake3:3SVIlI_M9KY1_kE_BUuxqP2L_JM1rAYj3LaY98lxNrM
1776461928587184	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtMQ		item.create	bn-2z1	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nLoad-bearing incremental behavior: when an input changes, only that input's downstream dependents should rebuild. Everything else is a no-op.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Compare current input hashes against previous `state/hashes.json`\n- Walk graph forward from changed nodes to collect stale set\n- Prompt template changes propagate to all dependent artifacts\n- Model version changes (recorded in BuildRecord) also invalidate — catches \"same prompt, new model\"\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Second compile with no changes rebuilds zero artifacts\n- [ ] Changing one source rebuilds only that source's page and dependent concepts\n- [ ] Changing a prompt template rebuilds only artifacts that used it\n- [ ] Changing the default model invalidates affected artifacts (or at least flags them stale)","kind":"task","parent":"bn-14j","title":"Stale detection: minimal stale set from changed inputs"}	blake3:xIFKOP9C-8DGHt7pGUs5hXs1Y5p5ZocdQI-FpkRqlH4
1776461928756184	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtMg		item.create	bn-3rb	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nExecutes compile passes in the documented order: normalize → metadata/summary → source pages → concept extraction → concept merge → backlinks/indexes → lint → optional outputs.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Pass registry: each pass declares (name, inputs, outputs, impl function)\n- Orchestrator walks stale set in topological order\n- Per-pass BuildRecord emitted with inputs, outputs, prompt hash, model, timestamp\n- Failures isolate to the failing pass; downstream passes are marked `stale` but not attempted\n- `--dry-run` lists what would rebuild without executing\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Passes execute in correct order\n- [ ] Failure in one pass does not corrupt manifest for others\n- [ ] BuildRecord emitted per pass\n- [ ] `--dry-run` lists the stale set","kind":"task","parent":"bn-14j","title":"Pass orchestrator (topological execution of stale set)"}	blake3:zC7YFXT1ojz63cJ_XKQmLgn_9nK-P-83u8WOXCfGbjY
1776461928908499	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtMw		item.create	bn-3dy	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nFor each NormalizedDocument, generate a concise summary used by lexical index + source page body. This is the first LLM-driven pass.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Prompt template `prompts/summarize.md` with {{title}}, {{body}}, {{max_words}} variables\n- Calls `LlmAdapter::summarize_document`\n- Output: summary text + key headings/topics list\n- Stored as managed region in source page; also used by index\n- Includes citations back to source revision (e.g. `{source_revision_id, section_anchor}`)\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Each normalized doc produces a summary\n- [ ] Summary is reproducible given same inputs + same model\n- [ ] BuildRecord captures prompt hash + model name","kind":"task","parent":"bn-14j","title":"Source summary pass (LLM: summarize_document)"}	blake3:IY84yVsnwAjpfcrkH2vMWDOeSsceeKAHszP0hIEKedI
1776461929065265	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtNA		item.create	bn-2xl	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nOne wiki page per source, containing managed regions for title/summary/key topics, plus frontmatter with source metadata. Human can read this page and see what the KB knows about a given source.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Frontmatter: id, type=source, title, source_document_id, source_revision_id, generated_at, build_record_id\n- Body sections in managed regions:\n  - `<!-- kb:begin id=summary -->` — LLM summary\n  - `<!-- kb:begin id=key_topics -->` — topic list\n  - `<!-- kb:begin id=citations -->` — list of backlinks / citations from concepts\n- Stable URL: `wiki/sources/<source-id-slug>.md`\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Page exists for each ingested source\n- [ ] Managed regions can be replaced in-place without clobbering\n- [ ] Frontmatter fields populated correctly","kind":"task","parent":"bn-14j","title":"Source page generator (wiki/sources/<id>.md)"}	blake3:ulbcHlAJZ3RTzPA5MZsCmFzuPtT1h59uAH--Frm_CcI
1776461929215250	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtNQ		item.create	bn-dnc	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nIdentifies candidate concept nodes from each source's body + summary. Canonicalization handled in a separate merge pass to keep concerns separated.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Prompt template `prompts/extract_concepts.md`\n- Output: list of `ConceptCandidate { name, aliases, definition_hint, source_anchors }`\n- Written to `state/concept_candidates/<source-id>.json` for the merge pass to consume\n- One LLM call per source; incremental (stale detection skips unchanged sources)\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Each source produces a candidate file\n- [ ] Candidates include aliases and anchors into the source\n- [ ] Incremental: unchanged sources skip re-extraction","kind":"task","parent":"bn-14j","title":"Concept extraction pass (LLM: extract_concepts)"}	blake3:tZFHIbLYZxDiM1ZhRxe80gZPUeqxDW0GVDEskKRa7LM
1776461929369915	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtNg		item.create	bn-36l	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPlan flags concept explosion as a real risk. Merge pass collapses synonyms, aliases, near-duplicates into canonical concept pages. Controversial merges go to `kb review`.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Load all candidate files into a global pool\n- LLM-assisted clustering: group candidates by proposed canonical name; flag uncertain merges for review\n- For confident merges, write `wiki/concepts/<slug>.md` with frontmatter listing aliases and source anchors\n- Uncertain merges → `reviews/merges/<merge-id>.json` for human approval\n- Preserve stable concept IDs across renames\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Same candidates produce same concept pages across runs\n- [ ] Uncertain merges land in review queue rather than silently merging\n- [ ] Aliases recorded so lookups can find a concept by any alias","kind":"task","parent":"bn-14j","title":"Concept merge + canonicalization (LLM: merge_concept_candidates)"}	blake3:cgXnSAwQvgqMM0DTBzlAEiwmXzyiP8829lS7wtGrgMA
1776461929529495	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtNw		item.create	bn-2i8	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nFor each concept, list the source pages and other concepts that reference it. Backlinks are what make the KB navigable in Obsidian.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Deterministic (no LLM): walk all wiki pages, parse `[[wiki-links]]` and anchor references\n- Build reverse index: target → list of referring pages\n- Emit managed backlink region at the bottom of each page\n- Update when dependent pages change (integrated into orchestrator)\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Every concept page has a backlinks section listing referring pages\n- [ ] Removing a reference updates the backlinks on next compile\n- [ ] No LLM calls in this pass","kind":"task","parent":"bn-14j","title":"Backlink regeneration"}	blake3:dXMk9HEnGXWLXc5KraHwFVXEdjDoe8vI7v-8G23iOFs
1776461929682985	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtOA		item.create	bn-2mw	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nGlobal index gives a read-only overview of the KB; per-category indexes (`wiki/sources/index.md`, `wiki/concepts/index.md`) provide navigation.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Deterministic generation from manifest data\n- `wiki/index.md` lists recent sources, top concepts, recent questions, unhealthy pages\n- Per-category indexes list their contents with summaries\n- All indexes are fully managed (no manual content mixed in)\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Global and per-category indexes exist after first compile\n- [ ] Indexes regenerate when contents change\n- [ ] Links from index to pages resolve","kind":"task","parent":"bn-14j","title":"Index page generation (wiki/index.md + category indexes)"}	blake3:zBlquAlPq_FEblSyax6EJK6t9Cj-x2glzrO3ToGCe_8
1776461929843399	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtOQ		item.create	bn-3dv	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nRetrieval backbone for `kb ask` and `kb search`. Plan explicitly defers full RAG infra; this simpler layered approach is enough for v1.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Tokenize titles, aliases, tags, summaries, key headings\n- Store under `state/indexes/lexical.json` (or sled/redb if JSON size becomes painful — defer that decision)\n- Ranking: token frequency + field weights (title > alias > heading > summary)\n- Regenerated on any wiki page change; kept small enough to load fully into memory\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Index builds after compile\n- [ ] `kb search` can query it\n- [ ] Ranking produces sensible top-K for obvious queries on the fixture corpus","kind":"task","parent":"bn-14j","title":"Lexical index over titles, aliases, summaries, headings"}	blake3:0BGa4Ouk9OED_WOhYHaZRyC8W6r_nAM7aUjyJGkEZp4
1776461930003653	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtOg		item.create	bn-2iu	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nEvery pass emits a BuildRecord linking outputs to their inputs, prompt, model, and timestamp. Inspectable via `kb inspect <id>`.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Stored under `state/build_records/<record-id>.json`\n- Referenced from each artifact's frontmatter via `build_record_id`\n- Includes: pass name, inputs (with hashes), outputs, prompt template hash, model, started_at, ended_at, status\n- Old records retained for audit; compaction later if size becomes painful\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Each generated artifact references a valid BuildRecord\n- [ ] `kb inspect <id>` can resolve from artifact to sources via records\n- [ ] Records survive across runs (no wiping on recompile)","kind":"task","parent":"bn-14j","title":"BuildRecord emission per pass"}	blake3:zvPJLj9gVYYqaRS66sxl5F-zluKbQxJqdpfDD7-kiBc
1776461930164626	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtOw		item.create	bn-30u	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nTies the passes, manifest, graph, and stale detection into the CLI. This is the primary command users will run repeatedly.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Runs under root lock + JobRun\n- Default: incremental (rebuild only stale)\n- `--force` flag for full rebuild\n- `--since <rev-or-time>` for selective rebuild of inputs changed since X\n- `--dry-run` lists what would rebuild\n- Progress output per pass with counts\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] No-op run is fast (<1s) and produces zero new BuildRecords\n- [ ] Full rebuild via `--force` works\n- [ ] `--dry-run` matches what the live run actually does","kind":"task","parent":"bn-14j","title":"kb compile command wiring + incremental guarantee"}	blake3:8S1YitRtQa4uogfJN2do7w7XY4VEEcVRCWrLWThiyAk
1776461969862280	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtPA		item.create	bn-2s3	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nQuestions are first-class tracked objects, not ephemeral chats. Each one gets a durable record.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `Question` record: id, timestamp, raw query, requested format (md/marp/json/png), requesting user context (project KB vs global)\n- Written to `outputs/questions/<question-id>/question.json` alongside the artifact\n- Referenced from the artifact's frontmatter\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Every `kb ask` invocation creates a Question record\n- [ ] Record survives across runs","kind":"task","parent":"bn-3b4","title":"Question record creation"}	blake3:TFZVhrY_XtBvsJIWjzlYkK2kRZ0gsXfPqGwPe8oKHWM
1776461970024260	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtPQ		item.create	bn-31a	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nDecides which sources and wiki pages to pull into context for the question. Saved plan makes it possible to debug why certain files were read.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Query the lexical index; rank candidates with field-weighted scores\n- Apply a token budget (configurable; default ~20k tokens)\n- Output: ordered candidate list with scores + reasons\n- Persist under `outputs/questions/<id>/retrieval_plan.json`\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Plan is deterministic for a given query + index state\n- [ ] Budget is respected\n- [ ] Plan includes per-candidate ranking reasons","kind":"task","parent":"bn-3b4","title":"Retrieval planner (rank candidates from lexical index)"}	blake3:_NZDjToS6eGQEQj11_zYebMl53dywktWCzrPW7I9uDc
1776461970185695	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtPg		item.create	bn-1c5	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nReads ranked candidates' full text (source.md, wiki page) into a single context string fed to the LLM. Must stay under budget while preserving citation anchors.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Iterate candidates top-down; include whole file if it fits, else extract summary + top-scoring sections\n- Wrap each chunk with a delimiter naming its source ID and section anchor (so the LLM can cite)\n- Produce context string + citation manifest mapping offsets → source locations\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Context stays under configured budget\n- [ ] Citation manifest lets post-processing resolve LLM citations to source anchors","kind":"task","parent":"bn-3b4","title":"Context assembly (pull top candidates into budget)"}	blake3:6fESUJBpVXaGNchzSyM3H0_XDZeRx4X2wXzNsaDSZJ8
1776461970343726	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtPw		item.create	bn-2zq	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nProduces the answer artifact. MVP format: markdown memo. Later: Marp slides, JSON report, plot data spec.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Prompt template `prompts/answer_markdown.md` with {{question}}, {{context}}, {{citation_manifest}}\n- Prompt explicitly requires citations for non-obvious claims\n- Post-process LLM output to validate citations resolve to the manifest\n- Degrade gracefully: if grounding is weak, add an uncertainty banner rather than inventing content\n- Suggest 1-3 follow-up questions in a separate managed region\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Produces a markdown memo on the fixture corpus\n- [ ] Each non-trivial claim has at least one citation\n- [ ] Unresolvable citations are flagged, not silently dropped\n- [ ] Uncertainty banner appears when retrieval is weak","kind":"task","parent":"bn-3b4","title":"Artifact generator (markdown memo format, LLM: answer_question)"}	blake3:xJBaurC9zsGYr7M39TTPikMGhBn42TYKnZ53CU-47dY
1776461970499840	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtQA		item.create	bn-88l	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nWrites the final artifact with frontmatter + provenance sidecar. Both are read later by lint, inspect, publish.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `outputs/questions/<question-id>/answer.md` with frontmatter: id, type=question_answer, question_id, generated_at, generated_by, build_record_id, source_document_ids, source_revision_ids\n- Sidecar: `outputs/questions/<question-id>/metadata.json` with the full provenance record and retrieval plan reference\n- Atomic writes; interrupted writes never leave half-files\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Artifact + sidecar + question record all coexist under `outputs/questions/<id>/`\n- [ ] Frontmatter includes all provenance fields\n- [ ] Interrupted write leaves no partial artifact","kind":"task","parent":"bn-3b4","title":"Artifact writer (outputs/questions/<id>.md + sidecar)"}	blake3:-8WAP7LPXQuy8SMGAv3sNUvZoG4U4tAQkoRawD8zw1s
1776461970656316	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtQQ		item.create	bn-zz7	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nEnd-user command that drives the planner → context → generator → writer pipeline.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `kb ask <question>` accepts question as positional arg or via stdin for longer prompts\n- `--format md|marp|json` selects artifact type (md only for MVP; others post-MVP)\n- `--promote` flag drops a ReviewItem to propose promotion into `wiki/`\n- `--dry-run` prints the retrieval plan without calling LLM\n- Runs under JobRun; no root lock (read-only of wiki, writes only under `outputs/`)\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `kb ask \"why X?\"` produces an answer file on the fixture corpus\n- [ ] `--dry-run` shows the retrieval plan\n- [ ] `--promote` creates a ReviewItem","kind":"task","parent":"bn-3b4","title":"kb ask command wiring"}	blake3:pGgBl1l7eqb5f_U6l0A7A1pPWntRYZJPIltbIBWVsNk
1776461970814828	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtQg		item.create	bn-lvq	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nExposes the same lexical index that drives retrieval, so the user can debug why a question reached specific sources.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `kb search <query>` returns top-K candidates with scores + reasons\n- `--json` emits structured results\n- `--limit N` tunes result count (default 10)\n- No LLM calls\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `kb search \"topic\"` returns ranked candidates\n- [ ] Scores and ranking reasons are displayed\n- [ ] Works on the fixture corpus deterministically","kind":"task","parent":"bn-3b4","title":"kb search command (lexical, debug aid)"}	blake3:gQpw12Co1oJm38j5--4kx7uC60VJB2dmfFfPUxM_vYk
1776461970963738	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtQw		item.create	bn-ud1	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nFull provenance chain view: from output back to source revisions and generating jobs. Central tool for debugging \"why does this page look the way it does?\"\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Given any ID (source, revision, wiki page, concept, question, artifact, build record), resolve and pretty-print:\n  - Metadata\n  - Dependency edges (from graph.json)\n  - Citations (from the page body)\n  - Generating JobRuns and BuildRecords\n  - Current freshness status\n- `--json` for structured output\n- `--trace` walks the full provenance chain recursively\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Works for every entity type\n- [ ] `--trace` produces readable chain output\n- [ ] Handles missing IDs with an actionable error","kind":"task","parent":"bn-3b4","title":"kb inspect <id> command"}	blake3:npV3tiFCgUjImDpJ0Z61VNtB2Y0ex6yyTSmUf4KRBJA
1776462007815357	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtRA		item.create	bn-est	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nWiki pages reference other wiki pages and source anchors. A moved or deleted target produces a broken link; lint surfaces these.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Parse `[[wiki-links]]`, markdown links, and citation anchors from every wiki page\n- Resolve each against the manifest + section ID registry\n- Report unresolvable targets with the referring page + line number\n- Fix-suggestions where possible (nearest matching title)\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Finds broken wiki-to-wiki links\n- [ ] Finds broken wiki-to-source anchor references\n- [ ] Output includes referring page + line + suggested fix","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1ji","title":"Broken-link checker"}	blake3:AV2Vu4m4f-eQFjrZu8d7v2AgiVwlSqJr25sc0Le764k
1776462007970917	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtRQ		item.create	bn-3by	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nProvenance is the central product risk. Lint should fail or warn when synthesized pages lose their source grounding.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- For each managed region marked as \"synthetic\" (vs \"extractive\"), check that the frontmatter source lists are non-empty and citations exist in the body\n- Report sections that claim LLM origin but cite nothing\n- Threshold configurable: warn vs error\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Synthetic section without citations triggers a warning\n- [ ] Extractive sections without citations are allowed (they ARE the source)\n- [ ] Threshold (warn/error) configurable via kb.toml","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1ji","title":"Missing-citation checker (synthesized sections must cite)"}	blake3:Ac3-N7OohabdWpp77M2zDPqnd4OpkEcRGmTjnqcRjsw
1776462008134305	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtRg		item.create	bn-1bp	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nConcept explosion is a named risk. If two concepts are near-duplicates and the merge pass did not catch them, lint should flag for review.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Compare concept titles + aliases across all concept pages\n- Flag pairs above a similarity threshold (fuzzy string match + shared source overlap)\n- Emit ReviewItems for flagged pairs rather than merging silently\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Near-duplicate concepts produce review items\n- [ ] Threshold tunable\n- [ ] Zero duplicates on clean fixture corpus","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1ji","title":"Duplicate concept / title warnings"}	blake3:U4E8HUpNOfKkXBuTXzMYXHgb6mhSXWcGtES4gy6HSX8
1776462008289482	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtRw		item.create	bn-1gg	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nOrphans = pages with no inbound references or whose source has been removed. Stale derived artifacts = outputs whose inputs have changed but were not rebuilt.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Walk manifest + graph; find pages whose source_document_ids no longer exist or whose source revisions are no longer referenced\n- Find artifacts where input hash does not match any current BuildRecord\n- Report both categories; `--json` supported for tooling\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Orphan pages flagged after source deletion\n- [ ] Stale artifacts flagged when manifest hashes diverge from disk","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1ji","title":"Orphan page + stale derived artifact detection"}	blake3:lHQkX5osLfBJa3C8a77vaIgpfxNuSdWcRZvaq21Rrb8
1776462008443812	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtSA		item.create	bn-2tg	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nJobRuns in status=running whose pid is no longer alive are interrupted. Detection is needed both from `kb doctor` and at the start of any mutating command.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Scan `state/jobs/` for running JobRuns\n- For each, check if the recorded pid is alive on this host\n- Mark stale ones as interrupted; describe the affected outputs in the next `kb status` / `kb doctor`\n- Recovery: mostly rerun `kb compile`; for Phase 3 answers, re-ask\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] A killed compile is detected on next invocation\n- [ ] Status message tells the user what to do","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1ji","title":"Interrupted-job detection and recovery guidance"}	blake3:Vxt5kGzXfb7OK15RctY7I5rTWaa-lR6Xvx1Wzh3W47A
1776462008607382	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtSQ		item.create	bn-9ac	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nRuns all lint checks and produces a single report.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `kb lint` runs every enabled check in order\n- `--check <name>` runs a single check\n- `--json` for structured output\n- Exit code: 0 if clean, 1 if warnings, 2 if errors (configurable per check)\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Runs all checks\n- [ ] Report groups findings by severity + check\n- [ ] Exit code reflects severity","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1ji","title":"kb lint command wiring"}	blake3:4h2ZsKOirQv4t4dO6p33sai2fm_sB_rQg5Uaj1cUA3k
1776462008761748	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtSg		item.create	bn-2j4	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nQuick orientation for the user: how much is in the KB, is anything stale, what has the tool done recently.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Sections: source count by type, wiki page count, concept count, stale count, recent JobRuns, failed jobs, changed inputs not yet compiled\n- `--json` for tooling\n- Fast: reads from manifest + state, no LLM calls\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Runs in well under a second on the fixture corpus\n- [ ] Shows stale counts accurately","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1ji","title":"kb status command (counts, freshness, recent jobs)"}	blake3:WwE3rtYjKM7P3v4zhYhkWuJrSDiW-Q9lg56j351MPdo
1776462008922876	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtSw		item.create	bn-3ka	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nSelf-diagnosis: validates config, checks that harnesses are installed, verifies filesystem permissions, confirms prompt templates load.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\nChecks:\n- `kb.toml` parses\n- KB root is writable\n- `opencode` and/or `claude` binaries on PATH\n- `LlmAdapter::run_health_check()` succeeds for configured backends\n- Prompt template directory exists and loads\n- No known interrupted jobs\n\nEach check reports OK / WARN / ERROR with a remediation hint.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] All checks covered\n- [ ] Missing harness is caught and remediation suggested\n- [ ] Exit code: 0 OK, 1 warn, 2 error","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1ji","title":"kb doctor command (config, model access, perms, tools)"}	blake3:ehbyepJVPodBGSqUFc7fUy4U2Fq8Zl_PgcIwqKugZdo
1776462060047222	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtTA		item.create	bn-1s1	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPlan is explicit: generated output is not automatically trusted. ReviewItems gate promotion of `outputs/` artifacts into `wiki/`, as well as concept merges and title canonicalization changes.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `ReviewItem` struct: id, kind (promotion | concept_merge | alias_merge), proposed destination, citations, affected pages, created_at, status\n- Stored under `reviews/<kind>/<id>.json`\n- Creation paths: `kb ask --promote`, concept merge pass for uncertain merges, duplicate lint for near-dupes\n- Rejected items marked rejected (not re-suggested for the same input hash)\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Creating a ReviewItem writes a file under `reviews/`\n- [ ] Rejected items stay rejected on subsequent runs with unchanged inputs\n- [ ] Items list affected pages so reviewer knows what's about to change","kind":"task","parent":"bn-3dc","title":"ReviewItem queue (promotions, merges, alias cleanup)"}	blake3:MVCyr-UD5_so6Gc0ryXXGXerO1NiRdOVJf7vNg_jsE8
1776462060201285	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtTQ		item.create	bn-31y	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nInteractive surface for going through review queue.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `kb review` lists pending items with counts by kind\n- `kb review show <id>` prints the proposed change with a diff preview\n- `kb review approve <id>` executes the change through the managed-region contract\n- `kb review reject <id>` marks rejected\n- `--json` for tooling\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] All three actions work end-to-end\n- [ ] Approve produces the same result as if compile had promoted the item itself\n- [ ] Reject leaves the artifact in place but marks the review record","kind":"task","parent":"bn-3dc","title":"kb review command (inspect, approve, reject)"}	blake3:ifp0oRtTW6bCN9IVz7y6fgBUinSo-vvm6V1xP-9_bGc
1776462060358171	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtTg		item.create	bn-1ox	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nWhen a ReviewItem is approved, the artifact content moves into the relevant wiki page's managed region. Must not clobber other managed regions or manual content.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Parse destination page's existing managed regions\n- Replace only the target region; preserve everything else\n- Update frontmatter source_document_ids and citations\n- Emit a BuildRecord so the promotion is traceable\n- Atomic write\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Promoted content lands in the right managed region\n- [ ] Untouched regions are byte-stable\n- [ ] BuildRecord reflects the promotion","kind":"task","parent":"bn-3dc","title":"Promotion writer (outputs/ → wiki/ via managed-region contract)"}	blake3:7F8SyevasnPS1ZS71IiKFB3bfjxdsyc4hMWsd_RoZDk
1776462060523009	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtTw		item.create	bn-1w3	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPlan envisions publishing selected artifacts into a project's `notes/` folder while preserving backlinks to the main KB.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- `[publish.targets]` section of kb.toml defines named targets: `{ path, filter, format }`\n- `kb publish <target>` copies selected artifacts with rewritten links back to the source KB\n- Use symlinks or copies (configurable); default copies for portability\n- Backlinks rewritten to absolute paths or URLs\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Configured target can be published in one command\n- [ ] Backlinks resolve after publish\n- [ ] Re-publishing is idempotent","kind":"task","parent":"bn-3dc","title":"kb publish <target>: sync to project notes/"}	blake3:41I7zZV46RHPInLhnfOlmbRZj5n7y2tDN6oFusjTVsQ
1776462060685052	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtUA		item.create	bn-1pf	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nFor agent harness integration, every command should support `--json` with a stable, documented schema. Chief's runner pattern already consumes tools this way.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Define a top-level envelope: `{ schema_version, command, data, warnings, errors }`\n- Each command's `data` shape versioned; breaking changes bump schema_version\n- Write the schema to `docs/cli-json-schema.md`\n- CI test that snapshot-checks the JSON output against the schema\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `kb <anything> --json` produces the envelope\n- [ ] Schema is documented\n- [ ] Snapshot tests cover the main commands","kind":"task","parent":"bn-3dc","title":"Stable CLI JSON output schema across commands"}	blake3:pctJIKaIrxG5SuJQSXG0oVvkqIz5HCDmYam_AHAcpnU
1776462060849223	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtUQ		item.create	bn-dgg	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nExplicit v1 non-goal: no full Obsidian plugin. But a thin wrapper that exposes `kb ask`, `kb inspect`, `kb compile` as Obsidian commands via the built-in Obsidian URI handler is a cheap ergonomic win.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Small Obsidian plugin (TypeScript) that shells out to `kb` in the vault's root\n- Three commands: Compile, Ask (prompt for input), Inspect current file\n- Use Obsidian's `editor.replaceSelection()` to drop output back into notes\n- Published as an unlisted plugin, not submitted to the community gallery\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Plugin installs and registers three commands\n- [ ] Compile reports status in the Obsidian status bar\n- [ ] Ask inserts result at cursor","kind":"task","parent":"bn-3dc","title":"(Deferred) Thin Obsidian command wrapper"}	blake3:Ih3t7RhzxAUWxB2cjxIbK5DPy0GD-3WrExojEvNSTQk
1776462061009201	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtUg		item.create	bn-37g	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPlan calls for a small benchmark of gold questions with expected citation sets, against one real corpus (private, not the fixture corpus).\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Curate ~20 questions the user actually cares about from their own notes corpus\n- For each: expected answer shape + expected citation set (which source(s) should be cited)\n- Store under `tests/gold/` (gitignored if the corpus is private)\n- Harness: run `kb ask` against each question, compare citations to expected set\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] At least 20 questions with expected citations\n- [ ] Harness scores citation coverage + hallucination rate\n- [ ] Baseline run recorded","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1lv","title":"Build gold question set on a real corpus"}	blake3:CfcEWpu4ecaI2DuXAMOPt-0aaeDGIexf37u6inq0eGg
1776462061170163	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtUw		item.create	bn-3a6	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nPlan target: compile/recompile fast enough that the user keeps the tool in their loop.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- Benchmark script on the real corpus: full rebuild, no-op incremental, one-source-changed incremental\n- Record p50/p95 runtime\n- Track per-pass timing (already available via `--timing` if implemented)\n- Results checked into `docs/perf/baseline.md`\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Three measured scenarios\n- [ ] Incremental no-op is under 1s\n- [ ] One-source-changed is proportionally faster than full rebuild","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1lv","title":"Measure compile + incremental rebuild time"}	blake3:boIsdkmUOCE2a7Kl5NylGVXXvXWzMV0rs9uV4pAtLZk
1776462061329802	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtVA		item.create	bn-9wg	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nCentral product risk: weak answers that look polished. Measurement is how we catch this.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- On gold questions, score:\n  - Citation coverage: fraction of non-trivial claims with valid citations\n  - Hallucination: claims that cannot be supported by any cited source\n  - Uncertainty handling: does the artifact flag weak grounding rather than invent?\n- Automated where possible; manual review for harder categories\n- Recorded alongside the perf baseline\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Metrics defined and documented\n- [ ] Baseline measured on gold set\n- [ ] Thresholds set for \"ship\" quality","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1lv","title":"Measure answer grounding quality"}	blake3:OmNQrPyz7I3WhqrAvHikURtkP7TTn7Db3spOSi2obDg
1776462061482064	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtVQ		item.create	bn-fb1	{"description":"# Context & Background\n\nFirst pass of prompts will have failure modes. Iterate based on observed failures from the gold question set.\n\n# Implementation Approach\n\n- For each failing question or hallucination, categorize the failure (retrieval miss, bad prompt, model weakness, context budget)\n- Patch prompts where the failure mode is \"bad prompt\"\n- Adjust retrieval ranking or budget where the failure mode is \"retrieval miss\"\n- Re-run gold set; record delta\n- At least one iteration before declaring v1 ready\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Failure analysis documented\n- [ ] At least one prompt iteration applied\n- [ ] Re-run metrics improve on baseline","kind":"task","parent":"bn-1lv","title":"Tune prompt templates + invalidation rules"}	blake3:wbZncKL3t2yYQ_lOCFqBg_6vZm7w4JG6LfOaRg-MTeo
